wZY|\"Cherish the Day\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Cherish the Day'''\" is a song by English band [[Sade (band)|Sade]] from their fourth studio album, ''[[Love Deluxe]]'' (1992). It was released as the album's fourth and final single in the United Kingdom on 17 July 1993 and in the United States on 11 September 1993. \n\n==Reception==\n''[[Music & Media]]'' wrote, \"Despite the artwork, showing Sade with a guitar and a stack of speakers in the background, she hasn't rocked up her sound. On the contrary, with a lonely drum track on a synth carpet, \"ambient soul\" is within reach.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/90s/1993/MM-1993-08-07.pdf|title=New Releases: Singles|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|volume=10|issue=32|page=7|date=7 August 1993|accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> Tanya Rena Jefferson of [[AXS (company)|AXS]] stated, \"This joyous soulful song embraces one to cherish each and every day.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Jefferson |first=Tanya Rena |url=https://www.axs.com/sade-s-10-best-songs-47376 |title=Sade's 10 best songs |website=[[AXS (company)|AXS]] |date=2 April 2015 |accessdate=21 June 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426130707/http://www.axs.com/sade-s-10-best-songs-47376 |archivedate=26 April 2016}}</ref> Sophie Heawood of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented \"The band at their most abstractly evocative: at their best, they could do a remarkable amount with very little \u2013 as proved by this song, during which immense yearning is conveyed.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Heawood |first=Sophie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/mar/13/why-sade-bigger-adele-us |title=Why Sade is bigger in the US than Adele |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=13 March 2012 |accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> Frank Guan of [[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]] added, \"Her minimalist lyrics... say all that needs to be said, and once a ten-note bassline jumps in to underscore her depth of feeling over the misty synths, the song is perfect and complete.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Guan |first=Frank |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/10/all-73-sade-songs-ranked-from-worst-to-best.html |title=All 73 Sade Songs, Ranked From Worst to Best |website=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]] |date=26 October 2017 |accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nFilmed in black and white by Derek M. Allen, the music video for \"Cherish the Day\" features [[Sade (singer)|Sade Adu]] performing the song whilst playing the guitar on the rooftop of a New York City skyscraper as her bandmates and a few other people vibe to the music on the streets below.\n\n==Track listings==\n*'''UK, European and Japanese CD single'''\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Sade remix short version) \u2013 5:18\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Sade remix long version) \u2013 6:18\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Ronin remix) \u2013 6:58\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Pal Joey remix) \u2013 6:46\n\n*'''US CD single'''\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Sade remix) \u2013 6:18\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Ronin remix) \u2013 6:58\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Pal Joey remix) \u2013 6:46\n#\"[[Feel No Pain]]\" ([[Nellee Hooper]] remix) \u2013 5:09\n#\"[[No Ordinary Love]]\" (album version) \u2013 7:18\n\n*'''Australian CD single / US cassette single'''\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Sade remix) \u2013 6:18\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Ronin remix) \u2013 6:58\n#\"Cherish the Day\" (Pal Joey remix) \u2013 6:46\n\n*'''UK and Dutch 12-inch single'''\n:A1. \"Cherish the Day\" (Sade remix long version) \u2013 6:18\n:A2. \"Cherish the Day\" (Ronin remix) \u2013 6:58\n:B1. \"Cherish the Day\" (Pal Joey remix) \u2013 6:46\n:B2. \"Cherish the Day\" (Sade remix short version) \u2013 5:18\n\n*'''US limited-edition 12-inch single'''\n:A1. \"Cherish the Day\" (Sade remix long version) \u2013 6:18\n:A2. \"Cherish the Day\" (Ronin remix) \u2013 6:58\n:B1. \"Cherish the Day\" (Pal Joey remix) \u2013 6:46\n:B2. \"Feel No Pain\" (Nellee Hooper remix) \u2013 5:09\n:B3. \"No Ordinary Love\" (album edit) \u2013 5:23\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1993)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://i.imgur.com/NqdaJXC.jpg |title=Response from ARIA re: Sade ARIA singles chart history, received 19 September 2017 |accessdate=19 September 2017 |via=[[Imgur]]}}</ref>\n| 207\n|-\n{{single chart|UKsinglesbyname|53|artist=Sade|artistid=21427|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 September 2017}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardbubbling100|16|artist=Sade|rowheader=true|accessdate=28 December 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/sade/chart-history/DSA |title=Sade Chart History (Dance Singles Sales) |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n| 23\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrandbhiphop|45|artist=Sade|rowheader=true|accessdate=28 December 2019}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|sade|cherish-the-day}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Sade}}\n\n[[Category:1990s ballads]]\n[[Category:1992 songs]]\n[[Category:1993 singles]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white music videos]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Sophie Muller]]\n[[Category:Sade (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Mike Pela]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sade Adu]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Stuart Matthewman]]\n[[Category:Trip hop songs]]\n", "name_user": "Jacksonpanix", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrack listings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cherish_the_Day"}
{"title_page": "Fanaa (2006 film)", "text_new": "{{redirect|Fanaa (film)|the 2010 film|Fanaa (2010 film)}}\n{{short description|2006 film by Kunal Kohli}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Fanaa\n| image          = Fanaa Poster.jpg\n| caption        = Movie Poster\n| director       = [[Kunal Kohli]]\n| producer       = [[Aditya Chopra]]\n| writer         = Kunal Kohli <small>'''(Dialogue)'''</small>\n| screenplay     = [[Shibani Bathija]]\n| story          = Shibani Bathija\n| starring       = [[Aamir Khan]]<br />[[Kajol]]<br />[[Rishi Kapoor]]<br />[[Kirron Kher]]<br />[[Sharat Saxena]]<br />[[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br />[[Jatin-Lalit]]<br />'''Score:'''<br />[[Salim-Sulaiman]]\n| cinematography = [[Ravi K. Chandran]]\n| editing        = Ritesh Soni\n| studio         = Yash Raj Films\n| distributor    = [[Yash Raj Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2006|05|26|df=y|India}}\n| runtime        = 169 minutes\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = {{INR}}30 [[crore]]<ref name=\"boxofficeindia1\">[https://www.boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=297 Fanaa]. Box Office India.</ref>\n| gross          = {{INR}}101\u2013105 crore<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Worldwide Grossers ALL TIME: 37 Films Hit 110 Crore|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3997&nCat=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030094721/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3997&nCat=|archive-date=30 October 2013|publisher=[[Box Office India]] |access-date=3 February 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/rs-2-200-cr-in-14-years-is-aamir-khan-the-real-badshah-of-bollywood/story-W6HfcunQcalsmvw2uUvomM.html|title=Rs. 2,200 cr in 14 years: Is Aamir Khan the real badshah of Bollywood?|work=m.hindustantimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"boxofficeindia1\" />\n}}\n\n'''''Fanaa''''' ({{trans|Destroyed in Love}}) is a 2006 [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Bollywood|Hindi-language]] [[romantic thriller]] film, directed by [[Kunal Kohli]] and produced by [[Yash Raj Films]]. The film stars [[Aamir Khan]] and [[Kajol]], with [[Rishi Kapoor]], [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]], [[Kirron Kher]] and [[Sharat Saxena]] in supporting roles.\n\nKhan plays the role of a tourist guide in [[New Delhi]] named Rehan Khan, while Kajol plays a blind [[Kashmiri people|Kashmiri]] woman, Zooni Ali Beg. Both fall in love, but are separated by a [[terrorist attack]] that reportedly kills Rehan. It is later revealed that he was not killed, but is in fact a [[Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir|Kashmiri insurgent]] whose real name is Rehan Qadri, and is the mastermind behind the attacks. Seven years later, his organization, known as the \"IKF\", sends him on a mission in [[Kashmir]], where he once again, in a strange fate, meets Zooni.\n\n''Fanaa'' was [[List of most expensive Indian films|one of the most expensive Bollywood films]] during its time of release. The film's title is derived from the [[Islam]]ic [[Sufism|Sufi]] term \"[[Fanaa (Sufism)|fanaa]]\", meaning \"destroyed\" in [[Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu]], and [[Hindi]]. Khan and Kajol were put into a romantic pairing for the first time with this film. It also marked the comeback of Kajol, who was last seen in ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' (2001).\n\n''Fanaa'' was released on 26 May 2006. The film was banned in the state of [[Gujarat]] due to protests against Aamir Khan for his comments criticising the [[Government of Gujarat|Gujarat government]]. Nevertheless, ''Fanaa'' received positive reviews and became a commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/aamir-khan-enters-brazil-with-fanaa/story-mAY8gThpbCzriIFzn8BnGJ.html|title=Aamir Khan enters Brazil with Fanaa|work=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=28 August 2012|accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Plot==\nZooni Ali Beg ([[Kajol]]) is a blind [[Kashmiris|Kashmiri]] woman who travels for the first time with her friends, Mehbooba ([[Sanaya Irani]]), Rubina ([[Gautami Kapoor]]) and Fatimah ([[Shruti Seth]]) to [[New Delhi]] to perform in a ceremony for [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]]. On her journey, she meets Rehan Khan ([[Aamir Khan]]), a tour guide who flirts with her. Although her friends warn Zooni about him, she falls in love. On her last night in Delhi, Rehan and Zooni spend the night together and end up in bed. As Zooni is leaving the next day, Rehan comes and takes her away with him. Her parents arrive in Delhi to marry them. Zooni has a procedure done that helps her see again, but when she comes out of surgery, she finds out that Rehan was killed in a bomb blast in the city.\n\nMalini Tyagi ([[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]]) is a special intelligence agent brought in to assess the threat of the bomb blast, and the group responsible, an independent organization fighting for an independent Kashmir known as IKF. It is revealed that Rehan is the man who placed the bomb blast in motion, then faked his death so Zooni wouldn't come looking for him. He admits that he loves Zooni, but also concedes that he can never see her again because of his dangerous life.\n\nSeven years later, Rehan is on another mission for the IKF. IKF has acquired a nuclear weapon but needs to get hold of the trigger, which is in the army's possession. Rehan steals it, but Tyagi has figured out his plan and sends forces to stop him. In the ensuing shootout, Rehan is injured. He makes his way to a remote house for help. It turns out to be Zooni's house. Zooni had become pregnant after Rehan's supposed death and has given birth to and raised her and Rehan's son. Zooni and her father save Rehan, though neither knows his real identity. Though initially distant from them, Rehan develops an affection for his son and the family.\n\nRehan eventually reveals his true identity to them. Initially hurt, Zooni refuses to let Rehan leave her again, and the two of them are married by her father. Tyagi has a report published about Rehan, warning the public that he is a [[terrorist]]. Zooni's father sees this report and confronts Rehan. Rehan accidentally throws Zooni's father off a ledge, killing him. He radios the IKF from an army officer's house but kills the officer when he discovers Rehan.\n\nZooni finds her father's body, and Rehan lies about his death. However, Zooni later sees the news report, and finds the trigger. She takes her son and flees to the officer's house, where she radios for help. Tyagi tells her to stop Rehan. Rehan arrives the next day, and takes the trigger from Zooni, saying the IKF will kill her and their son if he doesn't. Zooni shoots him in the leg. Rehan draws his gun on her, but can't bring himself to shoot. Zooni shoots him again, this time fatally, to stop him. Tyagi stops the IKF from shooting Zooni. Rehan dies in Zooni's arms.\n\nZooni and her son later visit the graves of her father and Rehan, who are buried next to each other. When her son asks if his father was wrong, Zooni tells him that his father did what he thought was right.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Aamir Khan]] as Rehan Qadri Sr. / Khan\n* [[Kajol]] as Zooni Ali Beg / Zooni Rehan Qadri \n* [[Rishi Kapoor]] as Zulfikar Ali Beg\n* [[Kirron Kher]] as Nafisa Ali Beg\n* [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]] as Malini Tyagi (Anti Terrorist Special Force)\n* [[Sanaya Irani]] as Mehbooba 'Boboo'\n* [[Gautami Kapoor]] as Rubina 'Ruby'\n* [[Shruti Seth]] as Fatimah 'Fatty'\n* [[Sharat Saxena]] as Susheel Rawat (Anti Terrorist Special Force)\n* Ahmed Khan as Naana Jaan (Rehan's Grandfather)\n* [[Satish Shah]] as Colonel Maan Singh        \n* Puneet Vasishtha as Captain Ijaz Khan\n* [[Jaspal Bhatti]] as Jolly Singh\n* [[Lilette Dubey]] as Helen\n* [[Vrajesh Hirjee]] as Balwant (Tourist Guide)\n* [[Suresh Menon]] as Venkateshwar Atti Cooper Rao\n* Shishir Sharma as Defence Minister\n* Salim Shah as Defence Secretary\n* Deepak Saraf as Chief Minister\n* [[Ali Haji (actor)|Ali Haji]] as Rehan Qadri Jr.\n* [[Shiney Ahuja]] as Major Suraj Ahuja (Special Appearance)\n* [[Lara Dutta]] as Zeenat (Special Appearance) \n{{colend}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{expand section|date=December 2016|reason=Where are the review excerpts?}}\nAt [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 100% rating critical approval rating, based on seven reviews.<ref>[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1194626_fanaa Fanaa (2006)]. Rotten Tomatoes. Retrieved on 14 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe performances from the leads, [[Aamir Khan]] and [[Kajol]], as well as their on-screen chemistry<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |author= hindi Shayari. |title= Hindi Love Shayari |url= https://www.magicalhindishayari.in |date= 29 May 2006 |work= Hindi Shayri Adda |accessdate= 26 August 2009 }}{{|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |author= Adarsh, Taran |title= Fanaa |url= http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/review/12456/index.html |date= 26 May 2006 |publisher= Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=26 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= Verma, Sukanya |title= Watch Fanaa for Aamir, Kajol! |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/may/26fansuk.htm|date= 26 May 2006 |publisher=Rediff |accessdate=26 August 2009}}</ref> were praised.The movie is hit and is an emotional love story well received by the audience .\n\n== Production ==\n{{empty section|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Filming locations===\n''Fanaa'' was originally planned to be shot in [[Kashmir]] before the lead actress backed out due to the continuing insurgency in that region. The director chose to move the Kashmir segment to the [[Tatra Mountains]] in southern [[Poland]], which also provides suitably snowy and mountainous terrain. It was filmed at historical locations in Delhi including the [[Delhi Fort|Red Fort]], [[Jantar Mantar]], [[Qutub Minar]], [[Purana Qila]], [[Rashtrapati Bhavan]] and [[Lodhi Gardens]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=156141 |title= Delhi monuments get starring role in Yash Chopra film |accessdate= 15 December 2008 |author= Vishnoi, Anubhuti |date= 8 November 2005 |work= [[The Indian Express]] }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nWhile promoting the film in [[Gujarat]], [[Aamir Khan]] made some comments regarding the Gujarat chief minister [[Narendra Modi]]'s handling of the [[Narmada Dam]] and the necessity to rehabilitate the displaced villagers.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://ia.rediff.com/news/2006/may/14aamir.htm |title= Aamir Khan slams Narendra Modi |accessdate=15 December 2008 |date= 14 June 2006 |publisher= [[Rediff]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/article2612165.ece |title= Film banned over star's dam protest |access-date= 15 December 2008 |author= Prasad, Raekha |date= 26 May 2006 |work= [[The Times]] |location= London |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150517161826/http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/article2612165.ece |archive-date= 17 May 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref> These comments were met with outrage from the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]. The government of Gujarat demanded an apology from Khan. Khan refused to apologise, saying \"I am saying exactly what the Supreme Court has said. I only asked for rehabilitation of poor farmers. I never spoke against the construction of the dam. I will not apologise for my comments on the issue.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/may/25aamir1.htm |title=Aamir on Narmada: I won't apologise |accessdate=15 December 2008 |author= Singh, Ankar |date= 25 May 2006 |work= [[Rediff]] }}</ref> An unofficial ban of ''Fanaa'' was put in place for the entire state of Gujarat. Protests occurred against the film and Khan which included the burning of posters of the star in effigy. As a result, several multiplex owners stated that they could not provide security to customers. Thus, all theatre owners in Gujarat refused to screen the movie.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1577182.cms |title= Gujarat left out as world sees Fanaa |accessdate=15 December 2008 |date= 27 May 2006 |work= [[Times of India]] }}t</ref>\n\nProducer [[Aditya Chopra]] moved a petition to the Supreme Court of India asking them to direct the Gujarat government to provide protection to all cinema halls that wanted to screen the film, but was rejected.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/jun/05fanaa.htm |title= SC rejects Fanaa petition |accessdate=15 December 2008 |author= Singh, Onkar |date= 5 June 2006 |publisher= [[Rediff]]}}</ref> Their response was that if a cinema was concerned for their protection they could call on the police.\n\nAddressing the media, director [[Kunal Kohli]] said, \"All theatre owners or exhibitors who wish to release this film can request for protection and the government should extend support. We as filmmakers request all theatre owners of Gujarat to come forward and release the film. We have earned 470&nbsp;million (both domestic and overseas) in the first week and have lost approximately 6 to 70&nbsp;million of business in Gujarat. However it's not about money... it is about a principle. As a democratic country where Aamir has a right to say what he feels, even the people of Gujarat, who are protesting have the right to say what they feel&nbsp;... but in a democratic fashion, and not by burning posters and threatening people.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.indiafm.com/news/2006/06/05/7225/index.html |title= Fanaa finally cleared in Gujarat |accessdate=15 December 2008 |publisher= IndiaFM}}</ref>\n\nA single privately owned cinema in [[Jamnagar]], Gujarat, screened the movie with police protection despite the threats.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/jun/06fanaa.htm |title= Gujarat theatre screens Fanaa |accessdate=15 December 2008 |date= 6 June 2006 |publisher= [[Rediff]]}}</ref> It ran for over a week before being withdrawn again following a [[self-immolation]] bid by a man protesting against the screening. The man, Pravin Joshi, entered the bathroom of the theatre during intermission of one of the screenings and set himself on fire. He suffered 85% burns and succumbed to his wounds nine days later.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.hindu.com/2006/06/21/stories/2006062107441500.htm |title= Fanaa: man who immolated dies |accessdate=15 December 2008 |date= 26 June 2006 |work= [[The Hindu]] }}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Fanaa\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Jatin Lalit]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 2006\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Yash Raj Films|YRF Music]]\n| producer   = [[Jatin-Lalit]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = Planet Bollywood\n| rev1score = {{Rating|8|10}}<ref name=\"pb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planetbollywood.com/displayReview.php?id=052706042348 |title= Fanaa Music Review by Gaurav Sathe |publisher=Planet Bollywood |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe music of ''Fanaa'' was [[Salim Sulaiman]] and [[Jatin-Lalit]] with the former composing the score and the latter, the songs. The lyrics for songs were penned by [[Prasoon Joshi]]. Five songs are featured in the movie while the soundtrack contains seven songs. This was the last movie for which [[Jatin-Lalit]] composed as a duo (they split afterwards).<ref name=ghosh>{{cite web |url= http://www.hindu.com/2006/04/16/stories/2006041606180200.htm |title= `Fanaa' promises to keep audience tuned in to its music |accessdate=15 December 2008 |last= Ghosh |first= Lakshmi B. |date= 16 April 2006 |work= [[The Hindu]] }}</ref>\n\nGaurav Sathe of Planet Bollywood gave 8 stars stating, \"Jatin-Lalit's last offering doesn't give us a Dilwale Dulania Le Jayenge or a K3G, but it is still a notch higher than some of the run-off-the-mill music we've been hearing as of late.\"<ref name=\"pb\"/> According to the Indian trade website [[Box Office India]], the album sold 17,00,000 units.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Hits 2000\u20132009 (Figures in Units)|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=286&catName=MjAwMC0yMDA5|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624132928/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=286&catName=MjAwMC0yMDA5|archivedate=24 June 2010|publisher=[[Box Office India]]}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! SL.No\n! Song\n! Artist\n! Length\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Chand Sifarish\"\n| [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]], [[Kailash Kher]] \n| 04:37\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Mere Haath Main\"\n| [[Sonu Nigam]], [[Sunidhi Chauhan]], [[Sulaiman Merchant]], [[Kajol]], [[Aamir Khan]]\n| 04:48\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Des Rangila\"\n| [[Mahalakshmi Iyer]]\n| 05:18\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Dekho Na\"\n| [[Sonu Nigam]] & [[Sunidhi Chauhan]]\n| 05:24\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Chanda Chamke\"\n| [[Babul Supriyo]], [[Mahalakshmi Iyer]], Master Akshay Bhagwat, Aamir Khan, Kajol\n| 03:50\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Destroyed in Love\"\n| [[Instrumental]]\n| 04:52\n|-\n| 7\n| \"Fanaa For You\"\n| [[DJ Aqeel]]\n| 04:26\n|}\nAamir Khan and Kajol recite lines of poetry in \"Chanda Chamke\" and \"Mere Haath Mein\".<ref name=ghosh/>\n\n==Awards==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n{| class =\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award || Category || Recipient(s)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|'''[[52nd Filmfare Awards]]''' || [[Filmfare Best Actress Award|Best Actress]] || [[Kajol]]\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Best Male Playback Award|Best Male Playback]] || [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] and [[Kailash Kher]] \u2013 Chand Sifarish\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Best Lyricist Award|Best Lyricist]] || [[Prasoon Joshi]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|'''[[Zee Cine Awards]]''' || [[Zee Cine Award Best Actor- Female|Best Actress]] || [[Kajol]]\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Award Best Playback Singer- Male|Best Playback Singer- Male]] || [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] \u2013 Chand Sifarish\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|'''[[8th IIFA Awards]]''' || [[IIFA Best Lyricist Award|Best Lyricist]] || [[Prasoon Joshi]]\n|-\n| [[IIFA Best Male Playback Award|Best Male Playback]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]]\n|-\n| '''[[Star Screen Awards]]''' || [[Star Screen Award Best Male Playback|Best Male Playback]] \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|'''[[Bollywood Movie Awards]]''' || [[Bollywood Movie Award - Best Lyricist|Best Lyricist]] || [[Prasoon Joshi]]\n|-\n| [[Bollywood Movie Award - Best Playback Singer Male|Best Playback Singer Male]] || [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Bollywood}}\n* [[List of highest-grossing Bollywood films]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0439662|title=Fanaa}}\n* {{mojo title|id=fanaa|title=Fanaa }}\n\n{{Kunal Kohli}}\n{{Yash Raj Films}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fanaa (Film)}}\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2000s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2006 films]]\n[[Category:Yash Raj Films films]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in India]]\n[[Category:Films set in Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:2000s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Poland]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jatin\u2013Lalit]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Delhi]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Urdu-language films]]\n[[Category:Kashmir conflict in films]]\n[[Category:Films about blind people in India]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Kunal Kohli]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Fanaa (film)|the 2010 film|Fanaa (2010 film)}}\n{{short description|2006 film by Kunal Kohli}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Fanaa\n| image          = Fanaa Poster.jpg\n| caption        = Movie Poster\n| director       = [[Kunal Kohli]]\n| producer       = [[Aditya Chopra]]\n| writer         = Kunal Kohli <small>'''(Dialogue)'''</small>\n| screenplay     = [[Shibani Bathija]]\n| story          = Shibani Bathija\n| starring       = [[Aamir Khan]]<br />[[Kajol]]<br />[[Rishi Kapoor]]<br />[[Kirron Kher]]<br />[[Sharat Saxena]]<br />[[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br />[[Jatin-Lalit]]<br />'''Score:'''<br />[[Salim-Sulaiman]]\n| cinematography = [[Ravi K. Chandran]]\n| editing        = Ritesh Soni\n| studio         = Yash Raj Films\n| distributor    = [[Yash Raj Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2006|05|26|df=y|India}}\n| runtime        = 169 minutes\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = {{INR}}30 [[crore]]<ref name=\"boxofficeindia1\">[https://www.boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=297 Fanaa]. Box Office India.</ref>\n| gross          = {{INR}}101\u2013105 crore<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Worldwide Grossers ALL TIME: 37 Films Hit 110 Crore|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3997&nCat=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030094721/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3997&nCat=|archive-date=30 October 2013|publisher=[[Box Office India]] |access-date=3 February 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/rs-2-200-cr-in-14-years-is-aamir-khan-the-real-badshah-of-bollywood/story-W6HfcunQcalsmvw2uUvomM.html|title=Rs. 2,200 cr in 14 years: Is Aamir Khan the real badshah of Bollywood?|work=m.hindustantimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"boxofficeindia1\" />\n}}\n\n'''''Fanaa''''' ({{trans|Destroyed in Love}}) is a 2006 [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Bollywood|Hindi-language]] [[romantic thriller]] film, directed by [[Kunal Kohli]] and produced by [[Yash Raj Films]]. The film stars [[Aamir Khan]] and [[Kajol]], with [[Rishi Kapoor]], [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]], [[Kirron Kher]] and [[Sharat Saxena]] in supporting roles.\n\nKhan plays the role of a tourist guide in [[New Delhi]] named Rehan Khan, while Kajol plays a blind [[Kashmiri people|Kashmiri]] woman, Zooni Ali Beg. Both fall in love, but are separated by a [[terrorist attack]] that reportedly kills Rehan. It is later revealed that he was not killed, but is in fact a [[Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir|Kashmiri insurgent]] whose real name is Rehan Qadri, and is the mastermind behind the attacks. Seven years later, his organization, known as the \"IKF\", sends him on a mission in [[Kashmir]], where he once again, in a strange fate, meets Zooni.\n\n''Fanaa'' was [[List of most expensive Indian films|one of the most expensive Bollywood films]] during its time of release. The film's title is derived from the [[Islam]]ic [[Sufism|Sufi]] term \"[[Fanaa (Sufism)|fanaa]]\", meaning \"destroyed\" in [[Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu]], and [[Hindi]]. Khan and Kajol were put into a romantic pairing for the first time with this film. It also marked the comeback of Kajol, who was last seen in ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' (2001).\n\n''Fanaa'' was released on 26 May 2006. The film was banned in the state of [[Gujarat]] due to protests against Aamir Khan for his comments criticising the [[Government of Gujarat|Gujarat government]]. Nevertheless, ''Fanaa'' received positive reviews and became a commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/aamir-khan-enters-brazil-with-fanaa/story-mAY8gThpbCzriIFzn8BnGJ.html|title=Aamir Khan enters Brazil with Fanaa|work=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=28 August 2012|accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Plot==\nZooni Ali Beg ([[Kajol]]) is a blind [[Kashmiris|Kashmiri]] woman who travels for the first time with her friends, Mehbooba ([[Sanaya Irani]]), Rubina ([[Gautami Kapoor]]) and Fatimah ([[Shruti Seth]]) to [[New Delhi]] to perform in a ceremony for [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]]. On her journey, she meets Rehan Khan ([[Aamir Khan]]), a tour guide who flirts with her. Although her friends warn Zooni about him, she falls in love. On her last night in Delhi, Rehan and Zooni spend the night together and end up in bed. As Zooni is leaving the next day, Rehan comes and takes her away with him. Her parents arrive in Delhi to marry them. Zooni has a procedure done that helps her see again, but when she comes out of surgery, she finds out that Rehan was killed in a bomb blast in the city.\n\nMalini Tyagi ([[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]]) is a special intelligence agent brought in to assess the threat of the bomb blast, and the group responsible, an independent organization fighting for an independent Kashmir known as IKF. It is revealed that Rehan is the man who placed the bomb blast in motion, then faked his death so Zooni wouldn't come looking for him. He admits that he loves Zooni, but also concedes that he can never see her again because of his dangerous life.\n\nSeven years later, Rehan is on another mission for the IKF. IKF has acquired a nuclear weapon but needs to get hold of the trigger, which is in the army's possession. Rehan steals it, but Tyagi has figured out his plan and sends forces to stop him. In the ensuing shootout, Rehan is injured. He makes his way to a remote house for help. It turns out to be Zooni's house. Zooni had become pregnant after Rehan's supposed death and has given birth to and raised her and Rehan's son. Zooni and her father save Rehan, though neither knows his real identity. Though initially distant from them, Rehan develops an affection for his son and the family.\n\nRehan eventually reveals his true identity to them. Initially hurt, Zooni refuses to let Rehan leave her again, and the two of them are married by her father. Tyagi has a report published about Rehan, warning the public that he is a [[terrorist]]. Zooni's father sees this report and confronts Rehan. Rehan accidentally throws Zooni's father off a ledge, killing him. He radios the IKF from an army officer's house but kills the officer when he discovers Rehan.\n\nZooni finds her father's body, and Rehan lies about his death. However, Zooni later sees the news report, and finds the trigger. She takes her son and flees to the officer's house, where she radios for help. Tyagi tells her to stop Rehan. Rehan arrives the next day, and takes the trigger from Zooni, saying the IKF will kill her and their son if he doesn't. Zooni shoots him in the leg. Rehan draws his gun on her, but can't bring himself to shoot. Zooni shoots him again, this time fatally, to stop him. Tyagi stops the IKF from shooting Zooni. Rehan dies in Zooni's arms.\n\nZooni and her son later visit the graves of her father and Rehan, who are buried next to each other. When her son asks if his father was wrong, Zooni tells him that his father did what he thought was right.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Aamir Khan]] as Rehan Qadri Sr. / Khan\n* [[Kajol]] as Zooni Ali Beg / Zooni Rehan Qadri \n* [[Rishi Kapoor]] as Zulfikar Ali Beg\n* [[Kirron Kher]] as Nafisa Ali Beg\n* [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]] as Malini Tyagi (Anti Terrorist Special Force)\n* [[Sanaya Irani]] as Mehbooba 'Boboo'\n* [[Gautami Kapoor]] as Rubina 'Ruby'\n* [[Shruti Seth]] as Fatimah 'Fatty'\n* [[Sharat Saxena]] as Susheel Rawat (Anti Terrorist Special Force)\n* Ahmed Khan as Naana Jaan (Rehan's Grandfather)\n* [[Satish Shah]] as Colonel Maan Singh        \n* Puneet Vasishtha as Captain Ijaz Khan\n* [[Jaspal Bhatti]] as Jolly Singh\n* [[Lilette Dubey]] as Helen\n* [[Vrajesh Hirjee]] as Balwant (Tourist Guide)\n* [[Suresh Menon]] as Venkateshwar Atti Cooper Rao\n* Shishir Sharma as Defence Minister\n* Salim Shah as Defence Secretary\n* Deepak Saraf as Chief Minister\n* [[Ali Haji (actor)|Ali Haji]] as Rehan Qadri Jr.\n* [[Shiney Ahuja]] as Major Suraj Ahuja (Special Appearance)\n* [[Lara Dutta]] as Zeenat (Special Appearance) \n{{colend}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{expand section|date=December 2016|reason=Where are the review excerpts?}}\nAt [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 100% rating critical approval rating, based on seven reviews.<ref>[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1194626_fanaa Fanaa (2006)]. Rotten Tomatoes. Retrieved on 14 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe performances from the leads, [[Aamir Khan]] and [[Kajol]], as well as their on-screen chemistry<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |author= Jha, Subhash K. |title= Fanaa |url= http://movies.indiatimes.com/articleshow/msid-1587805,curpg-1.cms |date= 29 May 2006 |work= Indiatimes |accessdate= 26 August 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |author= Adarsh, Taran |title= Fanaa |url= http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/review/12456/index.html |date= 26 May 2006 |publisher= Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=26 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= Verma, Sukanya |title= Watch Fanaa for Aamir, Kajol! |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/may/26fansuk.htm|date= 26 May 2006 |publisher=Rediff |accessdate=26 August 2009}}</ref> were praised.The movie is hit and is an emotional love story well received by the audience .\n\n== Production ==\n{{empty section|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Filming locations===\n''Fanaa'' was originally planned to be shot in [[Kashmir]] before the lead actress backed out due to the continuing insurgency in that region. The director chose to move the Kashmir segment to the [[Tatra Mountains]] in southern [[Poland]], which also provides suitably snowy and mountainous terrain. It was filmed at historical locations in Delhi including the [[Delhi Fort|Red Fort]], [[Jantar Mantar]], [[Qutub Minar]], [[Purana Qila]], [[Rashtrapati Bhavan]] and [[Lodhi Gardens]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=156141 |title= Delhi monuments get starring role in Yash Chopra film |accessdate= 15 December 2008 |author= Vishnoi, Anubhuti |date= 8 November 2005 |work= [[The Indian Express]] }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nWhile promoting the film in [[Gujarat]], [[Aamir Khan]] made some comments regarding the Gujarat chief minister [[Narendra Modi]]'s handling of the [[Narmada Dam]] and the necessity to rehabilitate the displaced villagers.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://ia.rediff.com/news/2006/may/14aamir.htm |title= Aamir Khan slams Narendra Modi |accessdate=15 December 2008 |date= 14 June 2006 |publisher= [[Rediff]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/article2612165.ece |title= Film banned over star's dam protest |access-date= 15 December 2008 |author= Prasad, Raekha |date= 26 May 2006 |work= [[The Times]] |location= London |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150517161826/http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/article2612165.ece |archive-date= 17 May 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref> These comments were met with outrage from the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]. The government of Gujarat demanded an apology from Khan. Khan refused to apologise, saying \"I am saying exactly what the Supreme Court has said. I only asked for rehabilitation of poor farmers. I never spoke against the construction of the dam. I will not apologise for my comments on the issue.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/may/25aamir1.htm |title=Aamir on Narmada: I won't apologise |accessdate=15 December 2008 |author= Singh, Ankar |date= 25 May 2006 |work= [[Rediff]] }}</ref> An unofficial ban of ''Fanaa'' was put in place for the entire state of Gujarat. Protests occurred against the film and Khan which included the burning of posters of the star in effigy. As a result, several multiplex owners stated that they could not provide security to customers. Thus, all theatre owners in Gujarat refused to screen the movie.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1577182.cms |title= Gujarat left out as world sees Fanaa |accessdate=15 December 2008 |date= 27 May 2006 |work= [[Times of India]] }}t</ref>\n\nProducer [[Aditya Chopra]] moved a petition to the Supreme Court of India asking them to direct the Gujarat government to provide protection to all cinema halls that wanted to screen the film, but was rejected.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/jun/05fanaa.htm |title= SC rejects Fanaa petition |accessdate=15 December 2008 |author= Singh, Onkar |date= 5 June 2006 |publisher= [[Rediff]]}}</ref> Their response was that if a cinema was concerned for their protection they could call on the police.\n\nAddressing the media, director [[Kunal Kohli]] said, \"All theatre owners or exhibitors who wish to release this film can request for protection and the government should extend support. We as filmmakers request all theatre owners of Gujarat to come forward and release the film. We have earned 470&nbsp;million (both domestic and overseas) in the first week and have lost approximately 6 to 70&nbsp;million of business in Gujarat. However it's not about money... it is about a principle. As a democratic country where Aamir has a right to say what he feels, even the people of Gujarat, who are protesting have the right to say what they feel&nbsp;... but in a democratic fashion, and not by burning posters and threatening people.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.indiafm.com/news/2006/06/05/7225/index.html |title= Fanaa finally cleared in Gujarat |accessdate=15 December 2008 |publisher= IndiaFM}}</ref>\n\nA single privately owned cinema in [[Jamnagar]], Gujarat, screened the movie with police protection despite the threats.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/jun/06fanaa.htm |title= Gujarat theatre screens Fanaa |accessdate=15 December 2008 |date= 6 June 2006 |publisher= [[Rediff]]}}</ref> It ran for over a week before being withdrawn again following a [[self-immolation]] bid by a man protesting against the screening. The man, Pravin Joshi, entered the bathroom of the theatre during intermission of one of the screenings and set himself on fire. He suffered 85% burns and succumbed to his wounds nine days later.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.hindu.com/2006/06/21/stories/2006062107441500.htm |title= Fanaa: man who immolated dies |accessdate=15 December 2008 |date= 26 June 2006 |work= [[The Hindu]] }}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Fanaa\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Jatin Lalit]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 2006\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Yash Raj Films|YRF Music]]\n| producer   = [[Jatin-Lalit]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = Planet Bollywood\n| rev1score = {{Rating|8|10}}<ref name=\"pb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planetbollywood.com/displayReview.php?id=052706042348 |title= Fanaa Music Review by Gaurav Sathe |publisher=Planet Bollywood |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe music of ''Fanaa'' was [[Salim Sulaiman]] and [[Jatin-Lalit]] with the former composing the score and the latter, the songs. The lyrics for songs were penned by [[Prasoon Joshi]]. Five songs are featured in the movie while the soundtrack contains seven songs. This was the last movie for which [[Jatin-Lalit]] composed as a duo (they split afterwards).<ref name=ghosh>{{cite web |url= http://www.hindu.com/2006/04/16/stories/2006041606180200.htm |title= `Fanaa' promises to keep audience tuned in to its music |accessdate=15 December 2008 |last= Ghosh |first= Lakshmi B. |date= 16 April 2006 |work= [[The Hindu]] }}</ref>\n\nGaurav Sathe of Planet Bollywood gave 8 stars stating, \"Jatin-Lalit's last offering doesn't give us a Dilwale Dulania Le Jayenge or a K3G, but it is still a notch higher than some of the run-off-the-mill music we've been hearing as of late.\"<ref name=\"pb\"/> According to the Indian trade website [[Box Office India]], the album sold 17,00,000 units.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Hits 2000\u20132009 (Figures in Units)|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=286&catName=MjAwMC0yMDA5|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624132928/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=286&catName=MjAwMC0yMDA5|archivedate=24 June 2010|publisher=[[Box Office India]]}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! SL.No\n! Song\n! Artist\n! Length\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Chand Sifarish\"\n| [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]], [[Kailash Kher]] \n| 04:37\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Mere Haath Main\"\n| [[Sonu Nigam]], [[Sunidhi Chauhan]], [[Sulaiman Merchant]], [[Kajol]], [[Aamir Khan]]\n| 04:48\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Des Rangila\"\n| [[Mahalakshmi Iyer]]\n| 05:18\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Dekho Na\"\n| [[Sonu Nigam]] & [[Sunidhi Chauhan]]\n| 05:24\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Chanda Chamke\"\n| [[Babul Supriyo]], [[Mahalakshmi Iyer]], Master Akshay Bhagwat, Aamir Khan, Kajol\n| 03:50\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Destroyed in Love\"\n| [[Instrumental]]\n| 04:52\n|-\n| 7\n| \"Fanaa For You\"\n| [[DJ Aqeel]]\n| 04:26\n|}\nAamir Khan and Kajol recite lines of poetry in \"Chanda Chamke\" and \"Mere Haath Mein\".<ref name=ghosh/>\n\n==Awards==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n{| class =\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award || Category || Recipient(s)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|'''[[52nd Filmfare Awards]]''' || [[Filmfare Best Actress Award|Best Actress]] || [[Kajol]]\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Best Male Playback Award|Best Male Playback]] || [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] and [[Kailash Kher]] \u2013 Chand Sifarish\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Best Lyricist Award|Best Lyricist]] || [[Prasoon Joshi]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|'''[[Zee Cine Awards]]''' || [[Zee Cine Award Best Actor- Female|Best Actress]] || [[Kajol]]\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Award Best Playback Singer- Male|Best Playback Singer- Male]] || [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] \u2013 Chand Sifarish\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|'''[[8th IIFA Awards]]''' || [[IIFA Best Lyricist Award|Best Lyricist]] || [[Prasoon Joshi]]\n|-\n| [[IIFA Best Male Playback Award|Best Male Playback]