{"title_page": "BBC Persian Television", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox TV channel\n| name              = BBC Persian \n| logofile          = BBC News Persian Logo.jpg\n| logosize          = 250px\n| logocaption       = \n| logo2             = \n| launch            = {{Start date and age|2009|1|14|df=y}}\n| closed date       = \n| picture format    = [[720p60]] ([[16:9]] [[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| owner             = [[BBC]]\n| slogan            = \n| country           = [[Iran]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Tajikistan]]\n| language          = [[Persian language|Persian]]\n| broadcast area    = Nationwide\n| headquarters      = [[Broadcasting House]], [[London]]\n| former names      = \n| replaced names    = \n| replaced by names = \n| sister names      = [[List of BBC channels]]\n| web               = [https://www.bbc.co.uk/persian/ bbc.co.uk/persian]\n| terr serv 1      = [[Oqaab]]<br><small>(Afghanistan)</small>\n| terr chan 1      = Channel 15\n| sat serv 1        = [[Eutelsat 7B]] <small>(Europe, North Africa, Middle East, Iran, Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan)</small>\n| sat chan 1        = 10721 H / 22000 / 3/4\n| sat serv 2        = [[Hot Bird 13B]] <small>(Europe, Middle East, North Africa)</small>\n| sat chan 2        = 12322 H / 27500 / 5/6\n| sat serv 3        = [[Afghansat 1]] <small>(Middle East, Iran, Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan)</small>\n| sat chan 3        = 11294 V / 27500 / 3/4\n| sat serv 4        = [[Al Yah 1]] <small>(Middle East, Iran, Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan)</small>\n| sat chan 4        = 11996 V / 27500 / 5/6\n| cable serv 1      = \n| cable chan 1      = \n| online serv 1     = [[BBC Online]]\n| online chan 1     = [http://www.bbcpersian.com/tvlive]\n}}\n\n[[File:BBC Persian TV presenters Majid Afshar &amp; Rana Rahimpoor 2017.jpg|thumb|BBC Persian TV presenters Majid Afshar &amp; Rana Rahimpoor, 2017]]\n'''BBC Persian Television''' ({{lang-fa|\u062a\u0644\u0648\u06cc\u0632\u06cc\u0648\u0646 \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0633\u06cc \u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0633\u06cc}}) is the [[BBC]]'s [[Persian language]] [[news channel]] that was launched on 14 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7827574.stm|title=BBC Awaits response to Persian TV|publisher=BBC|date=2009-01-14|accessdate=2010-01-01|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220034018/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7827574.stm|archivedate=20 February 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The service is broadcast by satellite and is also available online.  It is aimed at the 120 million [[Persian language|Persian-speakers]] in [[Iran]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Tajikistan]], and [[Uzbekistan]]. \n\nIranian authorities have been known to harass and intimidate family members of the BBC Persian staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/commentisfree/2019/mar/17/irans-threats-to-bbc-persian-staff-must-be-confronted|title=Iran\u2019s threats to BBC Persian staff must be confronted|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> BBC director Mark Thompson said that the staff of BBC Persian had been subject to \"increased levels of intimidation alongside disturbing new tactics\" by the Iranian government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-16874177|title=Iran accused of intimidating BBC Persian staff|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe annual budget of \u00a315 million was funded by the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]],<ref name=\" The Times - the Persian gulf \">{{cite news |first= Minette|last= Marrin|url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/leading_article/article5512228.ece |title= Bridging the Persian gulf |publisher=The Times| location=London | date=2009-01-14 |accessdate= 2010-04-26}}</ref> but as with the [[BBC World Service]] which is also funded by the FCO, the BBC remains editorially independent,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/WS_Broadcasting_Agreement02FINAL.pdf|title=Broadcasting Agreement for the Provision of the BBC World Service|author1=Foreign and Commonwealth Office |author2=The British Broadcasting Corporation|date=2006-07-01|publisher=BBC/FCO|accessdate=2009-01-29| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090205170804/http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/WS_Broadcasting_Agreement02FINAL.pdf| archivedate= 5 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> though some Iranian media have accused the British Government of using the service as a propaganda tool.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zibb.com/article/4734334/Iranian+website+alleges+British+government+influence+in+BBC+Persian+TV|title=Iranian website alleges British government influence in BBC Persian TV|date=16 January 2009|publisher=ZIBB|accessdate=2009-01-29}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The Iranian government  issued a statement denouncing the new service as 'suspicious and illegal', and 'working against the interests of the Islamic Republic'.<ref name=\" The Times - the Persian gulf \"/> On 1 April 2014, all World Service funding transfers to the [[Television licensing in the United Kingdom|Licence Fee]] model, which is paid for by all UK residents who watch television as it is broadcast.\n\nAs of November 2017, BBC Persian has an audience of 13 million Iranians.<ref name=\"veconomist\">{{cite news|title=Why has Iran imprisoned Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe?|url=https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21731407-jailing-british-citizen-highlights-crackdown-journalists-home-and-abroad-why-has|accessdate=17 November 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|date=16 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117080245/https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21731407-jailing-british-citizen-highlights-crackdown-journalists-home-and-abroad-why-has|archivedate=17 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn June 2009, BBC Persian's [[Hot Bird]] satellite broadcasts along with those of [[BBC Arabic Television]], other BBC services, and those of other broadcasters were experiencing interference due to a jamming signal originating from within Iran.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.rnw.nl/medianetwork/bbc-says-its-satellite-broadcasts-being-disrupted-from-iran |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619195806/http://blogs.rnw.nl/medianetwork/bbc-says-its-satellite-broadcasts-being-disrupted-from-iran |archivedate=19 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }} BBC says its satellite broadcasts being disrupted from Iran</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.rnw.nl/medianetwork/bbc-adds-more-satellites-for-its-persian-tv-service |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528135435/http://blogs.rnw.nl/medianetwork/bbc-adds-more-satellites-for-its-persian-tv-service |archivedate=28 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }} BBC adds more satellites for its Persian TV service</ref><ref>http://www.spacenews.com/satellite_telecom/100108-france-seeks-itu-signal-jamming-iran.html</ref> In response, BBC Persian started transmission on other satellites and increased their broadcast hours in order to combat the interference<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jun/19/iran-bbc-worldwide | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Iran elections: BBC World Service battles satellite interference | first=Oliver | last=Luft | date=2009-06-19 | accessdate=2010-04-26 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906172308/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jun/19/iran-bbc-worldwide | archivedate=6 September 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe channel has been accused by Iranian state television of encouraging \"illegal\" rallies and manipulating the Iranian people against the Islamic Republic, a claim which the BBC denies.\n\nThe jamming resumed on 20 December 2009 soon after BBC Persian began extended coverage of the [[Timeline of the 2009 Iranian election protests#December|protests]] resulting from the death of leading reformist cleric Grand Ayatollah [[Hoseyn Ali Montazeri]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/12_december/21/persian.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-11-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104033148/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/12_december/21/persian.shtml |archivedate=4 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }} BBC Persian television broadcasting despite interference from Iran</ref> and on 28 December 2009, BBC Persian ceased its transmission from the Hot Bird 6 satellite.,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.kingofsat.net/channelhistory.php?ch=6262 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091224153655/http://en.kingofsat.net/channelhistory.php?ch=6262 |archivedate=24 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }} Kingofsat - \"2009-12-28 BBC Persian has left 11117.00MHz\"</ref> however transmissions continued from the [[Telstar 12]], [[W series (satellites)|Eutelsat W2M]] and [[Nilesat 103|Atlantic Bird]] 4A satellites.<ref name=\"en.kingofsat.net\">{{cite web |url=http://en.kingofsat.net/detail-bbcpersian.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116183547/http://en.kingofsat.net/detail-bbcpersian.php |archivedate=16 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }} Kingofsat - \"BBC Persian (All satellites)\"</ref>\n\nBBC Persian returned to a different frequency on Hot Bird 6 <ref name=\"provider,coverage\">{{cite web |url=http://widenetworks.net/hotbird.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120908051017/http://www.widenetworks.net/hotbird.html |archivedate=8 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }} \"(Hotbird Service Provider)\"</ref> on 26 May 2010, after a period of test transmissions.<ref name=\"en.kingofsat.net\"/> After a new jamming in February 2011 on Hotbird, BBC Persian showed for some months only a test card along with the audio of their service. Since February 2012 BBC Persian has resumed broadcasting on Hotbird again.\n\nDue to the ban on foreign reporters in Iran, the news service currently relies on a significant amount of user-generated content, often taken with mobile phones.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8113882.stm BBC Persian works round restrictions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626025415/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8113882.stm |date=26 June 2009 }}, BBC News, 2009-06-23.</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Iranian authorities seized the Iranian assets of 152 contributors to BBC Persian, while in 2016 they detained former [[BBC World Service Trust]] employee [[Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe]].<ref name=\"veconomist\" /><ref name=bbcma-20160705>{{cite web |url=http://mediacentre.trust.org/documents/bbcma-statement.pdf |title=In the matter of Nazanin Zaghari Ratcliffe and Iran |last=Nursey |first=Caroline |publisher=BBC Media Action |date=5 July 2016 |accessdate=19 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119003140/http://mediacentre.trust.org/documents/bbcma-statement.pdf |archivedate=19 November 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Iranian government has \"targeted\" the members and family members of BBC Persian through threats, intimidation, and arrests. In 2018 the BBC made a request to the UN Human Rights Council to \"stop Iran from harassing its Persian service staff in London and their families in Iran.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Women in Iran need America\u2019s help. Why won\u2019t we give it to them?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/10/08/women-iran-need-americas-help-why-wont-we-give-it-them/|accessdate=2010-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=BBC UN appeal: Stop Iran harassing Persian service staff|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-43334401|accessdate=2010-11-13}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIt appears that [[Iranian presidential election, 2009]] and what followed greatly elevated BBC Persian TV's stature and importance. It became the channel that extensively covered the events for the Iranians inside Iran.  Outside of Iran, the channel was therefore recognised accordingly.\n\nOn 4 November 2009, BBC Persian TV was honoured for the \"Clearest coverage of a single news event \u2013 television\" by the [[Association for International Broadcasting]] at its annual global media excellence awards at a gala event in [[London, England]]. The award was for \"the elections that shook Iran\".<ref>http://www.aib.org.uk/newsContent.asp?node_id=8,95&content_id=2047 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203071450/http://www.aib.org.uk/newsContent.asp?node_id=8%2C95&content_id=2047 |date=3 December 2010 }}</ref>  It was a half-hour narration of the unrest that developed in the streets of Iran immediately after the disputed June presidential elections.\n\nOn 20 November 2009, BBC Persian TV was honoured at the 12th annual [[Hot Bird TV Awards]] in [[Venice, Italy]]. It was named best news channel for its portrayal of unbiased news in a complex and fast-moving environment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/world/news/e3ied5661580e6e68a1de0af3144e35832b |url-status=dead |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Mimi |last=Turner |title=BBC Persian News tops Hot Bird nods |date=2009-11-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091123144420/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/world/news/e3ied5661580e6e68a1de0af3144e35832b |archivedate=23 November 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\nThe channel broadcasts live from studio 44D, a green screen studio in [[BBC Broadcasting House]], [[London]], for nine hours every day (13:30-22:30 GMT, 17:00-02:00 [[Tehran]] time). Studio 54D, BBC Persian's home since its launch, is currently being refurbished to enable HD programming and automation of studio equipment.\n\nRepeats of news and entertainment programmes, plus visualised radio bulletins, fill the remaining 15 hours. <ref name=\"BBC - Persian TV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/theeditors/2009/01/bbc_persian_tv.html|title=BBC Persian TV|publisher=BBC|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121113840/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/theeditors/2009/01/bbc_persian_tv.html|archivedate=21 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nProgrammes cover a variety of genres including current affairs, documentaries, light entertainment, culture, science, business and the arts.\nEntertainment programmes such as ''[[Sound (BBC TV series)|BBC Sound]]'', ''[[Sherlock (TV series)|Sherlock]]'', ''[[Glastonbury Festival]]'' and ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' are broadcast with Persian [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing]].<ref name=\"BBC - Persian TV\"/>\n\n==Presenters and Correspondents==\n\n; [[Jamaluddin Mousavi|Jamaluddin Mousavi (Mosawi)]]\nJamaluddin (Jamal) started working for the BBC in 2001 as a journalist when he joined the BBC's Central Asia magazine in Iran and Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/01_january/08/persian3.shtml|title=BBC - Press Office - Persian TV press pack: services|website=www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151231134332/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/01_january/08/persian3.shtml|archivedate=31 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Before joining the BBC, Jamal was the editor of a weekly publication for Afghan refugees living in Mashhad, the province capital of Iran's Khorasan province where he also managed a UNHCR project to train young Afghan journalists. Jamal comes from Afghanistan although he grew up and studied in Iran. Jamal is the lead presenter of the flagship 60 Minutes programme. \n\n;Rana Rahimpour\nRana presents both news bulletins and the 60 Minutes programme. She also regularly contributes to UN discussions around the treatment of BBC Persian members of staff. \n\n;Najieh Ghulami\nNajieh Ghulami was born in Afghanistan to a [[Tajiks|Tajik]] Herati mother and a [[Hazaras|Hazara]] kubuli father. She was three years old when her family moved to Iran in the wake of the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan. Najieh began her broadcasting career in 2001 as a reporter for the BBC Persian service in Mashhad: the capital of Khorasan province in northeast Iran. She was the first Persian-speaking journalist to be accredited by the Iranian government to work for the BBC in Iran.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1716_wagpersian09/page2.shtml|title=BBC World Service - World Agenda - BBC Persian TV|website=www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126092529/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1716_wagpersian09/page2.shtml|archivedate=26 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Farnaz Ghazizadeh\nFarnaz Ghazizadeh has worked for some of Iran's most respected newspapers, including ''Neshat'', ''Yas-e Nou'' and the weekly ''Zan'' (Woman). She began her broadcast career in 2000 as the presenter of a daily science programme for Iranian television. In December 2003 Farnaz emigrated to the Netherlands with her family, where she joined several other Iranian journalists to start the news website Roozonline. She joined BBC Persian in 2005 as a radio correspondent. She now presents Page 2, a twice-weekly politics discussion programme.\n\n; Majid Afshar\nMajid Afshar has worked for English language news network [[Press TV]] for 8 years before joining the BBC in 2014.\n\n;Baran Abbasi\nStarted presenting in 2018\n\n;Kasra Naji\nPreviously a correspondent for the channel, Naji now presents news bulletins.\n\n===Correspondents===\n\n; [[Nafiseh Kohnavard]]\nA reporter who covers conflict and political news from Turkey to Iraq especially the ISIS atrocities in Sinjar and other locations.\n\n;Behrang Tajdin\nBehrang covers technology and UK political stories for the Channel.\n\n;Jiyar Gol\nTurkey correspondent\n\n;Pooria Jafereh\nSports correspondent\n\n;Khashayar Joneidi\nWashington correspondent \n\n;Bahman Kalbasi\nUnited States/UN correspondent\n\n===Previous Presenters===\n\n; [[Fardad Farahzad]]\nFardad Farahzad is a news presenter and reporter with the BBC Persian TV. He has anchored and covered many major Iranian and international stories for the network, including Iran's Nuclear Program, Arab Spring, 2012 US Presidential Election, Brussels bombings and 2016 Nice attack.\n\n; Nader Soltanpour\nSoltanpour (in Persian \u0646\u0627\u062f\u0631 \u0633\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0646\u067e\u0648\u0631) is an Iranian-Canadian journalist and television news presenter with the BBC World-Persian service.\nSoltanpour studied finance in Montreal, Canada and for 10 years worked in banks and investment firms in Toronto, Canada.\nIn 1997, while still working in finance, Soltanpour began his journalism career as a producer and presenter of a weekly radio programme called Persian Voice (in Persian \u0631\u0627\u062f\u06cc\u0648 \u0635\u062f\u0627\u06cc\u200c \u067e\u0627\u0631\u0633\u06cc) for the Iranian and Afghan communities in Toronto, Canada. In 2000, Nader left finance and turned Persian Voice into Canada's first nightly Persian language radio programme. In 2005, he joined the  [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] as a copy writer and producer for The World Report, Canada's most-listened-to morning news programme. Nader joined BBC Persian television in July 2008.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n:\n\n==Programmes==\n*[[KOOK (TV series)]]\n*[[Persian Click (TV series)]]\n{{Portal|BBC}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite journal |author=Mitra M. Shahrani |title=BBC Persian: Filling the Media Void in the Persian-Speaking World |journal=Asian Politics & Policy |volume=6 |year=2014 |issue=2 |pages=335\u2013338 |doi=10.1111/aspp.12102}}\n\n==References==\n{{wikinews|News services and World Wide Web companies increase Farsi services after Iranian presidential election}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/persian/ bbc.co.uk/persian/]\n* [http://www.logect.com/content.php?r=402-bbc-persian-live-tv-online-stream  BBC Persian Live TV]\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-41750919 UN urges Iran to stop harassing BBC Persian staff]\n{{BBC News}}\n{{BBC Television}}\n{{BBC World Service}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bbc Persian Television}}\n[[Category:International BBC television channels]]\n[[Category:BBC News channels]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Persian-language television stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox TV channel\n| name              = BBC Persian \n| logofile          = BBC News Persian Televison.jpg\n| logosize          = 250px\n| logocaption       = \n| logo2             = \n| launch            = {{Start date and age|2009|1|14|df=y}}\n| closed date       = \n| picture format    = [[720p60]] ([[16:9]] [[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| owner             = [[BBC]]\n| slogan            = \n| country           = [[Iran]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Tajikistan]]\n| language          = [[Persian language|Persian]]\n| broadcast area    = Nationwide\n| headquarters      = [[Broadcasting House]], [[London]]\n| former names      = \n| replaced names    = \n| replaced by names = \n| sister names      = [[List of BBC channels]]\n| web               = [https://www.bbc.co.uk/persian/ bbc.co.uk/persian]\n| terr serv 1      = [[Oqaab]]<br><small>(Afghanistan)</small>\n| terr chan 1      = Channel 15\n| sat serv 1        = [[Eutelsat 7B]] <small>(Europe, North Africa, Middle East, Iran, Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan)</small>\n| sat chan 1        = 10721 H / 22000 / 3/4\n| sat serv 2        = [[Hot Bird 13B]] <small>(Europe, Middle East, North Africa)</small>\n| sat chan 2        = 12322 H / 27500 / 5/6\n| sat serv 3        = [[Afghansat 1]] <small>(Middle East, Iran, Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan)</small>\n| sat chan 3        = 11294 V / 27500 / 3/4\n| sat serv 4        = [[Al Yah 1]] <small>(Middle East, Iran, Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan)</small>\n| sat chan 4        = 11996 V / 27500 / 5/6\n| cable serv 1      = \n| cable chan 1      = \n| online serv 1     = [[BBC Online]]\n| online chan 1     = [http://www.bbcpersian.com/tvlive]\n}}\n\n[[File:BBC Persian TV presenters Majid Afshar &amp; Rana Rahimpoor 2017.jpg|thumb|BBC Persian TV presenters Majid Afshar &amp; Rana Rahimpoor, 2017]]\n'''BBC Persian Television''' ({{lang-fa|\u062a\u0644\u0648\u06cc\u0632\u06cc\u0648\u0646 \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0633\u06cc \u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0633\u06cc}}) is the [[BBC]]'s [[Persian language]] [[news channel]] that was launched on 14 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7827574.stm|title=BBC Awaits response to Persian TV|publisher=BBC|date=2009-01-14|accessdate=2010-01-01|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220034018/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7827574.stm|archivedate=20 February 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The service is broadcast by satellite and is also available online.  It is aimed at the 120 million [[Persian language|Persian-speakers]] in [[Iran]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Tajikistan]], and [[Uzbekistan]]. \n\nIranian authorities have been known to harass and intimidate family members of the BBC Persian staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/commentisfree/2019/mar/17/irans-threats-to-bbc-persian-staff-must-be-confronted|title=Iran\u2019s threats to BBC Persian staff must be confronted|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> BBC director Mark Thompson said that the staff of BBC Persian had been subject to \"increased levels of intimidation alongside disturbing new tactics\" by the Iranian government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-16874177|title=Iran accused of intimidating BBC Persian staff|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe annual budget of \u00a315 million was funded by the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]],<ref name=\" The Times - the Persian gulf \">{{cite news |first= Minette|last= Marrin|url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/leading_article/article5512228.ece |title= Bridging the Persian gulf |publisher=The Times| location=London | date=2009-01-14 |accessdate= 2010-04-26}}</ref> but as with the [[BBC World Service]] which is also funded by the FCO, the BBC remains editorially independent,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/WS_Broadcasting_Agreement02FINAL.pdf|title=Broadcasting Agreement for the Provision of the BBC World Service|author1=Foreign and Commonwealth Office |author2=The British Broadcasting Corporation|date=2006-07-01|publisher=BBC/FCO|accessdate=2009-01-29| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090205170804/http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/WS_Broadcasting_Agreement02FINAL.pdf| archivedate= 5 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> though some Iranian media have accused the British Government of using the service as a propaganda tool.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zibb.com/article/4734334/Iranian+website+alleges+British+government+influence+in+BBC+Persian+TV|title=Iranian website alleges British government influence in BBC Persian TV|date=16 January 2009|publisher=ZIBB|accessdate=2009-01-29}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The Iranian government  issued a statement denouncing the new service as 'suspicious and illegal', and 'working against the interests of the Islamic Republic'.<ref name=\" The Times - the Persian gulf \"/> On 1 April 2014, all World Service funding transfers to the [[Television licensing in the United Kingdom|Licence Fee]] model, which is paid for by all UK residents who watch television as it is broadcast.\n\nAs of November 2017, BBC Persian has an audience of 13 million Iranians.<ref name=\"veconomist\">{{cite news|title=Why has Iran imprisoned Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe?|url=https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21731407-jailing-british-citizen-highlights-crackdown-journalists-home-and-abroad-why-has|accessdate=17 November 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|date=16 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117080245/https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21731407-jailing-british-citizen-highlights-crackdown-journalists-home-and-abroad-why-has|archivedate=17 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn June 2009, BBC Persian's [[Hot Bird]] satellite broadcasts along with those of [[BBC Arabic Television]], other BBC services, and those of other broadcasters were experiencing interference due to a jamming signal originating from within Iran.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.rnw.nl/medianetwork/bbc-says-its-satellite-broadcasts-being-disrupted-from-iran |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619195806/http://blogs.rnw.nl/medianetwork/bbc-says-its-satellite-broadcasts-being-disrupted-from-iran |archivedate=19 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }} BBC says its satellite broadcasts being disrupted from Iran</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.rnw.nl/medianetwork/bbc-adds-more-satellites-for-its-persian-tv-service |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528135435/http://blogs.rnw.nl/medianetwork/bbc-adds-more-satellites-for-its-persian-tv-service |archivedate=28 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }} BBC adds more satellites for its Persian TV service</ref><ref>http://www.spacenews.com/satellite_telecom/100108-france-seeks-itu-signal-jamming-iran.html</ref> In response, BBC Persian started transmission on other satellites and increased their broadcast hours in order to combat the interference<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jun/19/iran-bbc-worldwide | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Iran elections: BBC World Service battles satellite interference | first=Oliver | last=Luft | date=2009-06-19 | accessdate=2010-04-26 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906172308/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jun/19/iran-bbc-worldwide | archivedate=6 September 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe channel has been accused by Iranian state television of encouraging \"illegal\" rallies and manipulating the Iranian people against the Islamic Republic, a claim which the BBC denies.\n\nThe jamming resumed on 20 December 2009 soon after BBC Persian began extended coverage of the [[Timeline of the 2009 Iranian election protests#December|protests]] resulting from the death of leading reformist cleric Grand Ayatollah [[Hoseyn Ali Montazeri]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/12_december/21/persian.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-11-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104033148/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/12_december/21/persian.shtml |archivedate=4 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }} BBC Persian television broadcasting despite interference from Iran</ref> and on 28 December 2009, BBC Persian ceased its transmission from the Hot Bird 6 satellite.,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.kingofsat.net/channelhistory.php?ch=6262 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091224153655/http://en.kingofsat.net/channelhistory.php?ch=6262 |archivedate=24 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }} Kingofsat - \"2009-12-28 BBC Persian has left 11117.00MHz\"</ref> however transmissions continued from the [[Telstar 12]], [[W series (satellites)|Eutelsat W2M]] and [[Nilesat 103|Atlantic Bird]] 4A satellites.<ref name=\"en.kingofsat.net\">{{cite web |url=http://en.kingofsat.net/detail-bbcpersian.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116183547/http://en.kingofsat.net/detail-bbcpersian.php |archivedate=16 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }} Kingofsat - \"BBC Persian (All satellites)\"</ref>\n\nBBC Persian returned to a different frequency on Hot Bird 6 <ref name=\"provider,coverage\">{{cite web |url=http://widenetworks.net/hotbird.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120908051017/http://www.widenetworks.net/hotbird.html |archivedate=8 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }} \"(Hotbird Service Provider)\"</ref> on 26 May 2010, after a period of test transmissions.<ref name=\"en.kingofsat.net\"/> After a new jamming in February 2011 on Hotbird, BBC Persian showed for some months only a test card along with the audio of their service. Since February 2012 BBC Persian has resumed broadcasting on Hotbird again.\n\nDue to the ban on foreign reporters in Iran, the news service currently relies on a significant amount of user-generated content, often taken with mobile phones.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8113882.stm BBC Persian works round restrictions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626025415/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8113882.stm |date=26 June 2009 }}, BBC News, 2009-06-23.</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Iranian authorities seized the Iranian assets of 152 contributors to BBC Persian, while in 2016 they detained former [[BBC World Service Trust]] employee [[Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe]].<ref name=\"veconomist\" /><ref name=bbcma-20160705>{{cite web |url=http://mediacentre.trust.org/documents/bbcma-statement.pdf |title=In the matter of Nazanin Zaghari Ratcliffe and Iran |last=Nursey |first=Caroline |publisher=BBC Media Action |date=5 July 2016 |accessdate=19 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119003140/http://mediacentre.trust.org/documents/bbcma-statement.pdf |archivedate=19 November 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Iranian government has \"targeted\" the members and family members of BBC Persian through threats, intimidation, and arrests. In 2018 the BBC made a request to the UN Human Rights Council to \"stop Iran from harassing its Persian service staff in London and their families in Iran.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Women in Iran need America\u2019s help. Why won\u2019t we give it to them?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/10/08/women-iran-need-americas-help-why-wont-we-give-it-them/|accessdate=2010-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=BBC UN appeal: Stop Iran harassing Persian service staff|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-43334401|accessdate=2010-11-13}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIt appears that [[Iranian presidential election, 2009]] and what followed greatly elevated BBC Persian TV's stature and importance. It became the channel that extensively covered the events for the Iranians inside Iran.  Outside of Iran, the channel was therefore recognised accordingly.\n\nOn 4 November 2009, BBC Persian TV was honoured for the \"Clearest coverage of a single news event \u2013 television\" by the [[Association for International Broadcasting]] at its annual global media excellence awards at a gala event in [[London, England]]. The award was for \"the elections that shook Iran\".<ref>http://www.aib.org.uk/newsContent.asp?node_id=8,95&content_id=2047 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203071450/http://www.aib.org.uk/newsContent.asp?node_id=8%2C95&content_id=2047 |date=3 December 2010 }}</ref>  It was a half-hour narration of the unrest that developed in the streets of Iran immediately after the disputed June presidential elections.\n\nOn 20 November 2009, BBC Persian TV was honoured at the 12th annual [[Hot Bird TV Awards]] in [[Venice, Italy]]. It was named best news channel for its portrayal of unbiased news in a complex and fast-moving environment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/world/news/e3ied5661580e6e68a1de0af3144e35832b |url-status=dead |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Mimi |last=Turner |title=BBC Persian News tops Hot Bird nods |date=2009-11-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091123144420/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/world/news/e3ied5661580e6e68a1de0af3144e35832b |archivedate=23 November 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\nThe channel broadcasts live from studio 44D, a green screen studio in [[BBC Broadcasting House]], [[London]], for nine hours every day (13:30-22:30 GMT, 17:00-02:00 [[Tehran]] time). Studio 54D, BBC Persian's home since its launch, is currently being refurbished to enable HD programming and automation of studio equipment.\n\nRepeats of news and entertainment programmes, plus visualised radio bulletins, fill the remaining 15 hours. <ref name=\"BBC - Persian TV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/theeditors/2009/01/bbc_persian_tv.html|title=BBC Persian TV|publisher=BBC|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121113840/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/theeditors/2009/01/bbc_persian_tv.html|archivedate=21 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nProgrammes cover a variety of genres including current affairs, documentaries, light entertainment, culture, science, business and the arts.\nEntertainment programmes such as ''[[Sound (BBC TV series)|BBC Sound]]'', ''[[Sherlock (TV series)|Sherlock]]'', ''[[Glastonbury Festival]]'' and ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' are broadcast with Persian [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing]].<ref name=\"BBC - Persian TV\"/>\n\n==Presenters and Correspondents==\n\n; [[Jamaluddin Mousavi|Jamaluddin Mousavi (Mosawi)]]\nJamaluddin (Jamal) started working for the BBC in 2001 as a journalist when he joined the BBC's Central Asia magazine in Iran and Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/01_january/08/persian3.shtml|title=BBC - Press Office - Persian TV press pack: services|website=www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151231134332/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/01_january/08/persian3.shtml|archivedate=31 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Before joining the BBC, Jamal was the editor of a weekly publication for Afghan refugees living in Mashhad, the province capital of Iran's Khorasan province where he also managed a UNHCR project to train young Afghan journalists. Jamal comes from Afghanistan although he grew up and studied in Iran. Jamal is the lead presenter of the flagship 60 Minutes programme. \n\n;Rana Rahimpour\nRana presents both news bulletins and the 60 Minutes programme. She also regularly contributes to UN discussions around the treatment of BBC Persian members of staff. \n\n;Najieh Ghulami\nNajieh Ghulami was born in Afghanistan to a [[Tajiks|Tajik]] Herati mother and a [[Hazaras|Hazara]] kubuli father. She was three years old when her family moved to Iran in the wake of the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan. Najieh began her broadcasting career in 2001 as a reporter for the BBC Persian service in Mashhad: the capital of Khorasan province in northeast Iran. She was the first Persian-speaking journalist to be accredited by the Iranian government to work for the BBC in Iran.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1716_wagpersian09/page2.shtml|title=BBC World Service - World Agenda - BBC Persian TV|website=www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126092529/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1716_wagpersian09/page2.shtml|archivedate=26 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Farnaz Ghazizadeh\nFarnaz Ghazizadeh has worked for some of Iran's most respected newspapers, including ''Neshat'', ''Yas-e Nou'' and the weekly ''Zan'' (Woman). She began her broadcast career in 2000 as the presenter of a daily science programme for Iranian television. In December 2003 Farnaz emigrated to the Netherlands with her family, where she joined several other Iranian journalists to start the news website Roozonline. She joined BBC Persian in 2005 as a radio correspondent. She now presents Page 2, a twice-weekly politics discussion programme.\n\n; Majid Afshar\nMajid Afshar has worked for English language news network [[Press TV]] for 8 years before joining the BBC in 2014.\n\n;Baran Abbasi\nStarted presenting in 2018\n\n;Kasra Naji\nPreviously a correspondent for the channel, Naji now presents news bulletins.\n\n===Correspondents===\n\n; [[Nafiseh Kohnavard]]\nA reporter who covers conflict and political news from Turkey to Iraq especially the ISIS atrocities in Sinjar and other locations.\n\n;Behrang Tajdin\nBehrang covers technology and UK political stories for the Channel.\n\n;Jiyar Gol\nTurkey correspondent\n\n;Pooria Jafereh\nSports correspondent\n\n;Khashayar Joneidi\nWashington correspondent \n\n;Bahman Kalbasi\nUnited States/UN correspondent\n\n===Previous Presenters===\n\n; [[Fardad Farahzad]]\nFardad Farahzad is a news presenter and reporter with the BBC Persian TV. He has anchored and covered many major Iranian and international stories for the network, including Iran's Nuclear Program, Arab Spring, 2012 US Presidential Election, Brussels bombings and 2016 Nice attack.\n\n; Nader Soltanpour\nSoltanpour (in Persian \u0646\u0627\u062f\u0631 \u0633\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0646\u067e\u0648\u0631) is an Iranian-Canadian journalist and television news presenter with the BBC World-Persian service.\nSoltanpour studied finance in Montreal, Canada and for 10 years worked in banks and investment firms in Toronto, Canada.\nIn 1997, while still working in finance, Soltanpour began his journalism career as a producer and presenter of a weekly radio programme called Persian Voice (in Persian \u0631\u0627\u062f\u06cc\u0648 \u0635\u062f\u0627\u06cc\u200c \u067e\u0627\u0631\u0633\u06cc) for the Iranian and Afghan communities in Toronto, Canada. In 2000, Nader left finance and turned Persian Voice into Canada's first nightly Persian language radio programme. In 2005, he joined the  [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] as a copy writer and producer for The World Report, Canada's most-listened-to morning news programme. Nader joined BBC Persian television in July 2008.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n:\n\n==Programmes==\n*[[KOOK (TV series)]]\n*[[Persian Click (TV series)]]\n{{Portal|BBC}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite journal |author=Mitra M. Shahrani |title=BBC Persian: Filling the Media Void in the Persian-Speaking World |journal=Asian Politics & Policy |volume=6 |year=2014 |issue=2 |pages=335\u2013338 |doi=10.1111/aspp.12102}}\n\n==References==\n{{wikinews|News services and World Wide Web companies increase Farsi services after Iranian presidential election}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/persian/ bbc.co.uk/persian/]\n* [http://www.logect.com/content.php?r=402-bbc-persian-live-tv-online-stream  BBC Persian Live TV]\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-41750919 UN urges Iran to stop harassing BBC Persian staff]\n{{BBC News}}\n{{BBC Television}}\n{{BBC World Service}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bbc Persian Television}}\n[[Category:International BBC television channels]]\n[[Category:BBC News channels]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Persian-language television stations]]\n", "name_user": "Wackedkid47", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BBC_Persian_Television"}
{"title_page": "The Light Is Coming", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 song by Ariana Grande featuring Nicki Minaj}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = The Light Is Coming\n| cover         = The Light Is Coming cover art.png\n| type          = promotional single\n| artist        = [[Ariana Grande]] featuring [[Nicki Minaj]]\n| album         = [[Sweetener (album)|Sweetener]]\n| released      = {{start date|2018|6|20}}\n| format        = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[streaming media|streaming]]}} \n| recorded      = 2017\n| studio        = {{hlist|Glenwood Place Studios  ([[Burbank, California]])|[[Jungle City Studios]] and Germano Studios ([[New York City]])|[[Chalice Recording Studios]] and [[Conway Recording Studios]] ([[Hollywood, California]])|The Lunchtable ([[Los Angeles, California]])}}\n| genre         = <!--do not add a genre without citing a source--> {{flatlist|\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]<ref name=\"new wave\"/>\n* [[Dance music|dance]]<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite web |last1=Daramola |first1=Israel |title=Ariana Grande\u2019s \"The Light Is Coming\" Is Hypnotic and Wonderfully Bizarre |url=https://www.spin.com/2018/06/ariana-grande-the-light-is-coming-nicki-minaj-review/ |website=[[Spin (magazine)|SPIN]] |accessdate=29 January 2020 |date=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| length        = 3:48\n| label         = [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| writer        = \n*[[Pharrell Williams]]\n*[[Nicki Minaj|Onika Maraj]]\n*Ariana Grande\n| producer      = Pharrell Williams\n| chronology = [[Ariana Grande]] [[Promotional singles]]\n| prev_title = Arturo Sandoval\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = [[Imagine (Ariana Grande song)|Imagine]] \n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc          = {{External music video|{{YouTube|OQitfe8u7i4|title=\"The Light Is Coming\"}}|type=song}}\n}}\n\n\"'''The Light Is Coming'''\" (stylized in [[Letter case#All lowercase|all lowercase]]) is a song by American singer [[Ariana Grande]], featuring American rapper [[Nicki Minaj]]. Both artists co-wrote the song with its producer [[Pharrell Williams]]. It was released on June 20, 2018, as the first promotional single from Grande's fourth studio album, ''[[Sweetener (album)|Sweetener]]''.<ref name=\"new wave\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/05/30/ariana-grande-cover-story|title=Cover Story: Ariana Grande|publisher=The Fader|last=Tanzer|first=Myles|date=May 30, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref> The track debuted at number 95 and peaked at number 89 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It reached the top 10 in Greece and New Zealand and peaked at number 12 in Japan.\n\n==Release==\nOn May 27, 2018, [[Ariana Grande]] teased \"The Light Is Coming\" with a 21-second clip on her Instagram page.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/05/ariana-grande-the-light-is-coming-nicki-minaj-teaser-listen/|title=Ariana Grande Teases New Song \"The Light Is Coming\" Featuring Nicki Minaj: Listen|date=May 28, 2018|work=Spin|accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref> On June 2, she debuted a preview of the song at Wango Tango, announcing that the song would be released on June 20, 2018, along with the pre-order of ''Sweetener''.<ref name=\"Rolling\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-ariana-grande-debut-the-light-is-coming-at-wango-tango-w521026|title=Watch Ariana Grande Debut New Song 'The Light Is Coming' at Wango Tango|work=Rolling Stone|date=June 3, 2018|accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref> The single artwork was shot by Photographer Alfredo Flores in New York City.\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\nThe song runs for three minutes and forty-eight seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/sweetener/1399202539|title=Sweetner by Ariana Grande|website=[[ITunes Store]]|date=June 20, 2018| accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref> It's a [[new wave]]<ref name=\"new wave\"/> and [[Dance music|dance]]<ref name=\"spin\" /> track with influences of [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]].<ref name=\"clashmusic\">{{cite web| url=http://www.clashmusic.com/news/ariana-grande-links-with-nicki-minaj-on-the-light-is-coming| title= Ariana Grande Links With Nicki Minaj On 'The Light Is Coming' |website=Clash Music|date=June 20, 2018| accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref> The sound is backed by Grande's vocals, singing, \"The light is coming to give back everything the darkness stole\". The song contains a \"jittery beat\" that is used with quick [[drum]]s and [[Synthesizer|synths]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/ariana-grande-taps-nicki-minaj-for-new-song-the-light-is-coming-listen/|title=Ariana Grande Taps Nicki Minaj for New Song \"The Light Is Coming\": Listen| date=June 20, 2018|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-ariana-grande-tap-nicki-minaj-for-snappy-the-light-is-coming-w521757| title=Hear Ariana Grande Tap Nicki Minaj for Snappy 'The Light Is Coming'| date=June 20, 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref> The song samples a [[CNN]] archive clip of a man named Craig Miller who is shouting at former senator [[Arlen Specter]] at a town hall meeting in Pennsylvania in 2009 concerning healthcare (\"You wouldn't let anybody speak for this and instead!\").<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.popbuzz.com/music/artists/ariana-grande/news/the-light-is-coming-sample-voice |title= Who Is The Man Sampled On Ariana Grande's 'The Light Is Coming'?|work= PopBuzz|accessdate= June 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8462197/ariana-grande-nicki-minaj-the-light-is-coming-vocal-sample|title=Ariana Grande's 'The Light Is Coming' Contains a Prominent Voice Sample With a Political Message| website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=June 21, 2018|accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref> Grande's vocals span 1 octave, from F#3 to G#4.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0191934 |title = The Light is Coming|date = December 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"The Light Is Coming\" received luke<!--per source-->warm reviews from music critics.<ref>{{cite web |last=Neid |first=Mike |title=Ariana Grande's \"God Is A Woman\" Is A Sexually Liberated Bop |url=http://www.idolator.com/7682674/ariana-grande-god-is-a-woman-listen?chrome=1 |website=Idolator |accessdate=July 13, 2018|date=July 13, 2018 }}</ref> Mike Nied of ''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'' described it as \"a serious dance floor filler\", writing: \"''The light is coming to give back everything the darkness stole'',\" [Grande] chants over militaristic drums and slippery synths. Her voice is confident and sounds perfectly at home as it races over the searing production, courtesy of [[Pharrell Williams|Pharrell]]. All things considered, it sounds like the pop princess has another hit on her hands.\"<ref name=\"idolator\">Nied, Mike.  [http://www.idolator.com/7681741/ariana-grande-nicki-minaj-the-light-is-coming-listen \"Banger! Ariana Grande & Nicki Minaj Bring The Heat On \u201cThe Light Is Coming\u201d\"], ''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'', June 23, 2018</ref> In the album review, however, Neid called it \"a particularly glaring misstep.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idolator.com/7684297/album-review-ariana-grande-sweetener?view-all&chrome=1 |title=Album Review: Ariana Grande's 'Sweetener' |work=Idolator}}</ref><nowiki> </nowiki>''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' editor Israel Daramola described the song as a \"glitchy, thumping\" [[Dance music|dance]] record with a sample that highlights Grande's \"nursery rhyme-style melody\" during the repeated chorus and her voice \"is alive with feeling and thrives in the quirks and constant vibrancy of the music.\" He also praised Minaj for delivering a \"strutting, paint-by-numbers verse in the time allotted\" that is \"perfectly suited to the heavy, ground shaking bass of the song\".<ref name=\"spin\"/> Brittany Spanos of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' considered it a \"weak spot\" in the parent album.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/review-ariana-grande-finds-serenity-and-has-some-fun-on-sweetener-713404/ |title=Review: Ariana Grande Finds Serenity and Has Some Fun on 'Sweetener' |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |date=August 20, 2018 |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"The Light Is Coming\" entered the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 95 selling 14,000 copies in its first week, allowing it to also debut on the [[Digital Songs]] chart at number 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/ariana-grande/chart-history/digital-song-sales|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=June 30, 2018|title=Ariana Grande Chart History}}</ref> The song fell off the Hot 100 the following week; however, it later re-entered at a new peak of number 89 following the release of  ''Sweetener''.<ref>Zellner, Xander. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8472538/ariana-grande-10th-top-10-hit-10-songs-billboard-hot-100-chart \"Ariana Grande Earns 10th Top 10 Hit, Lands 10 Songs on ''Billboard'' Hot 100\"], ''Billboard'', August 27, 2018</ref>\n\nWorldwide, the song debuted in the top-forty in Hungary and Scotland, peaking at numbers 24 and 22 respectively, while charting within the top 100 in six other territories including the United Kingdom, where it reached number 57 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. It also peaked at number 63 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]].\n\n==Music video==\nDespite the song not being released as an official single, the music video for the song first premiered twelve hours after the song's release, via the [[Reebok]] official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reebok.com/us/tlic|title=\"THE LIGHT IS COMING\" PREMIERE|accessdate=20 June 2018}}</ref> It was directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]], who had also directed the music video for Grande's \"[[No Tears Left to Cry]]\", and features \n[[Nicki Minaj]] performing her verse and [[Ariana Grande]] singing in a dimly-lit forest. The video was released worldwide on YouTube and Vevo the next day.\n\n==Live performances==\nGrande performed a preview of the song at [[Wango Tango]] on June 2, 2018 and was on the set list of her [[Sweetener World Tour]].<ref name=\"Rolling\"/>\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n'''Recording and management'''\n* Recorded at Glenwood Place Studios ([[Burbank, California]]), [[Jungle City Studios]] ([[New York City]]), [[Chalice Recording Studios]] ([[Hollywood]], [[California]]), The Lunchtable ([[Los Angeles]], California and [[Conway Recording Studios]] (Hollywood, California)\n* Nicki Minaj's vocals recorded at Germano Studios ([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])\n* Mastered at [[Sterling Sound]] (New York City, New York)\n* EMI Pop Music Publishing/More Water From Nazareth (GMR), Harajuku Barbie Music/Money Mack Music/Songs of Universal, Inc. (BMI), Universal Music Group Corp. (ASCAP)/GrandAriMusic (ASCAP)\n\n'''Personnel'''\n{{div col}}\n*[[Ariana Grande]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead vocals]], [[songwriting]]\n*[[Nicki Minaj]]&nbsp;\u2013 featured vocals, songwriting\n*[[Pharrell Williams]]&nbsp;\u2013 songwriting, [[music production|production]]\n*Mike Larson&nbsp;\u2013 [[audio recording|recording]], [[digital editing]], [[arrangement]], additional [[music programming|programming]]\n*Jacob Dennis&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Ramon Rivas&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Brendan Morawski&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Thomas Cullison&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Ben \u201cBengineer\u201d Sedano&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Aubry \u201cBig Juice\u201d Delaine&nbsp;\u2013 Nicki Minaj's vocals recording\n*Kris Crawford&nbsp;\u2013 Nicki Minaj's recording assistant\n*Manny Park&nbsp;\u2013 Nicki Minaj's recording assistant\n*[[Manny Marroquin]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[audio mixing|mixing]]\n*Scott Desmarais&nbsp;\u2013 mix assistant\n*Chris Galland&nbsp;\u2013 mix assistant\n*Robin Florent&nbsp;\u2013 mix assistant\n*Randy Merrill&nbsp;\u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''Photography'''\n\n* Alfredo Flores (cover art)\n\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Sweetener''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Sweetener|others=[[Ariana Grande]]|year=2018|publisher=[[Republic Records]]}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2018/6/aria-chart-watch-479/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #479|publisher=auspOp|date=June 30, 2018|accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| 60\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|63|artist=Ariana Grande|rowheader=true|accessdate=July 3, 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|France|70|artist=Ariana Grande feat. Nicki Minaj|song=The Light Is Coming|rowheader=true|accessdate=July 3, 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Greece Digital Songs (''[[Billboard Greece|Billboard]]'')<ref name=greekdigitalchartbillboard>{{cite web|title=Greece Digital Songs|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2018-06-30/greece-digital-song-sales|website=Billboard|accessdate=June 15, 2018|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| 2\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarysingle|24|year=2018|week=25|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n| 76\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Japan Hot Overseas (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=d_and_a_overseas&year=2018&month=07&day=16|title=Billboard Japan Hot Overseas|language=Japanese|website=[[Billboard Japan]]|date=July 16, 2018|accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| 12\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|81|artist=Ariana Grande feat. Nicki Minaj|song=The Light Is Coming|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand Heatseekers ([[Recorded Music NZ]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=4494|title=NZ Heatseeker Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=July 2, 2018|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| 2\n|-\n{{single chart|Portugaldigitalsongs|7|artist=Ariana Grande|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|22|date=20180622|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|57|date=20180629|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 30, 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|89|artist=Ariana Grande|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 28, 2018}}\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Worldwide \n| June 20, 2018\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://ArianaGrande.lnk.to/thelightiscoming|title=The Light Is Coming|accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ariana Grande songs}}\n{{Nicki Minaj songs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Light Is Coming}}\n[[Category:2018 songs]]\n[[Category:Ariana Grande songs]]\n[[Category:Nicki Minaj songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Pharrell Williams]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ariana Grande]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Nicki Minaj]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Pharrell Williams]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Dave Meyers (director)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 song by Ariana Grande featuring Nicki Minaj}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = The Light Is Coming\n| cover         = The Light Is Coming cover art.png\n| type          = promotional single\n| artist        = [[Ariana Grande]] featuring [[Nicki Minaj]]\n| album         = [[Sweetener (album)|Sweetener]]\n| released      = {{start date|2018|6|20}}\n| format        = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[streaming media|streaming]]}} \n| recorded      = 2017\n| studio        = {{hlist|Glenwood Place Studios  ([[Burbank, California]])|[[Jungle City Studios]] and Germano Studios ([[New York City]])|[[Chalice Recording Studios]] and [[Conway Recording Studios]] ([[Hollywood, California]])|The Lunchtable ([[Los Angeles, California]])}}\n| genre         = <!--do not add a genre without citing a source--> {{flatlist|\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]<ref name=\"new wave\"/>\n* [[Dance music|dance]]<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite web |last1=Daramola |first1=Israel |title=Ariana Grande\u2019s \"The Light Is Coming\" Is Hypnotic and Wonderfully Bizarre |url=https://www.spin.com/2018/06/ariana-grande-the-light-is-coming-nicki-minaj-review/ |website=[[Spin (magazine)|SPIN]] |accessdate=29 January 2020 |date=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| length        = 3:48\n| label         = [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| writer        = \n*[[Pharrell Williams]]\n*[[Nicki Minaj|Onika Maraj]]\n*Ariana Grande\n| producer      = Pharrell Williams\n| chronology = [[Ariana Grande]] [[Promotional singles]]\n| prev_title = Arturo Sandoval\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = [[Imagine (Ariana Grande song)|Imagine]] \n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc          = {{External music video|{{YouTube|OQitfe8u7i4|title=\"The Light Is Coming\"}}|type=song}}\n}}\n\n\"'''The Light Is Coming'''\" (stylized in [[Letter case#All lowercase|all lowercase]]) is a song by American singer [[Ariana Grande]], featuring American rapper [[Nicki Minaj]]. Both artists co-wrote the song with its producer [[Pharrell Williams]]. It was released on June 20, 2018, as the first promotional single from Grande's fourth studio album, ''[[Sweetener (album)|Sweetener]]''.<ref name=\"new wave\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/05/30/ariana-grande-cover-story|title=Cover Story: Ariana Grande|publisher=The Fader|last=Tanzer|first=Myles|date=May 30, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref> The track debuted at number 95 and peaked at number 89 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It reached the top 10 in Greece and New Zealand and peaked at number 12 in Japan.\n\n==Release==\nOn May 27, 2018, [[Ariana Grande]] teased \"The Light Is Coming\" with a 21-second clip on her Instagram page.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/05/ariana-grande-the-light-is-coming-nicki-minaj-teaser-listen/|title=Ariana Grande Teases New Song \"The Light Is Coming\" Featuring Nicki Minaj: Listen|date=May 28, 2018|work=Spin|accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref> On June 2, she debuted a preview of the song at Wango Tango, announcing that the song would be released on June 20, 2018, along with the pre-order of ''Sweetener''.<ref name=\"Rolling\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-ariana-grande-debut-the-light-is-coming-at-wango-tango-w521026|title=Watch Ariana Grande Debut New Song 'The Light Is Coming' at Wango Tango|work=Rolling Stone|date=June 3, 2018|accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\nThe song runs for three minutes and forty-eight seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/sweetener/1399202539|title=Sweetner by Ariana Grande|website=[[ITunes Store]]|date=June 20, 2018| accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref> It's a [[new wave]]<ref name=\"new wave\"/> and [[Dance music|dance]]<ref name=\"spin\" /> track with influences of [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]].<ref name=\"clashmusic\">{{cite web| url=http://www.clashmusic.com/news/ariana-grande-links-with-nicki-minaj-on-the-light-is-coming| title= Ariana Grande Links With Nicki Minaj On 'The Light Is Coming' |website=Clash Music|date=June 20, 2018| accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref> The sound is backed by Grande's vocals, singing, \"The light is coming to give back everything the darkness stole\". The song contains a \"jittery beat\" that is used with quick [[drum]]s and [[Synthesizer|synths]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/ariana-grande-taps-nicki-minaj-for-new-song-the-light-is-coming-listen/|title=Ariana Grande Taps Nicki Minaj for New Song \"The Light Is Coming\": Listen| date=June 20, 2018|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-ariana-grande-tap-nicki-minaj-for-snappy-the-light-is-coming-w521757| title=Hear Ariana Grande Tap Nicki Minaj for Snappy 'The Light Is Coming'| date=June 20, 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref> The song samples a [[CNN]] archive clip of a man named Craig Miller who is shouting at former senator [[Arlen Specter]] at a town hall meeting in Pennsylvania in 2009 concerning healthcare (\"You wouldn't let anybody speak for this and instead!\").<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.popbuzz.com/music/artists/ariana-grande/news/the-light-is-coming-sample-voice |title= Who Is The Man Sampled On Ariana Grande's 'The Light Is Coming'?|work= PopBuzz|accessdate= June 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8462197/ariana-grande-nicki-minaj-the-light-is-coming-vocal-sample|title=Ariana Grande's 'The Light Is Coming' Contains a Prominent Voice Sample With a Political Message| website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=June 21, 2018|accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref> Grande's vocals span 1 octave, from F#3 to G#4.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0191934 |title = The Light is Coming|date = December 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"The Light Is Coming\" received luke<!--per source-->warm reviews from music critics.<ref>{{cite web |last=Neid |first=Mike |title=Ariana Grande's \"God Is A Woman\" Is A Sexually Liberated Bop |url=http://www.idolator.com/7682674/ariana-grande-god-is-a-woman-listen?chrome=1 |website=Idolator |accessdate=July 13, 2018|date=July 13, 2018 }}</ref> Mike Nied of ''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'' described it as \"a serious dance floor filler\", writing: \"''The light is coming to give back everything the darkness stole'',\" [Grande] chants over militaristic drums and slippery synths. Her voice is confident and sounds perfectly at home as it races over the searing production, courtesy of [[Pharrell Williams|Pharrell]]. All things considered, it sounds like the pop princess has another hit on her hands.\"<ref name=\"idolator\">Nied, Mike.  [http://www.idolator.com/7681741/ariana-grande-nicki-minaj-the-light-is-coming-listen \"Banger! Ariana Grande & Nicki Minaj Bring The Heat On \u201cThe Light Is Coming\u201d\"], ''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'', June 23, 2018</ref> In the album review, however, Neid called it \"a particularly glaring misstep.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idolator.com/7684297/album-review-ariana-grande-sweetener?view-all&chrome=1 |title=Album Review: Ariana Grande's 'Sweetener' |work=Idolator}}</ref><nowiki> </nowiki>''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' editor Israel Daramola described the song as a \"glitchy, thumping\" [[Dance music|dance]] record with a sample that highlights Grande's \"nursery rhyme-style melody\" during the repeated chorus and her voice \"is alive with feeling and thrives in the quirks and constant vibrancy of the music.\" He also praised Minaj for delivering a \"strutting, paint-by-numbers verse in the time allotted\" that is \"perfectly suited to the heavy, ground shaking bass of the song\".<ref name=\"spin\"/> Brittany Spanos of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' considered it a \"weak spot\" in the parent album.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/review-ariana-grande-finds-serenity-and-has-some-fun-on-sweetener-713404/ |title=Review: Ariana Grande Finds Serenity and Has Some Fun on 'Sweetener' |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |date=August 20, 2018 |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"The Light Is Coming\" entered the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 95 selling 14,000 copies in its first week, allowing it to also debut on the [[Digital Songs]] chart at number 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/ariana-grande/chart-history/digital-song-sales|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=June 30, 2018|title=Ariana Grande Chart History}}</ref> The song fell off the Hot 100 the following week; however, it later re-entered at a new peak of number 89 following the release of  ''Sweetener''.<ref>Zellner, Xander. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8472538/ariana-grande-10th-top-10-hit-10-songs-billboard-hot-100-chart \"Ariana Grande Earns 10th Top 10 Hit, Lands 10 Songs on ''Billboard'' Hot 100\"], ''Billboard'', August 27, 2018</ref>\n\nWorldwide, the song debuted in the top-forty in Hungary and Scotland, peaking at numbers 24 and 22 respectively, while charting within the top 100 in six other territories including the United Kingdom, where it reached number 57 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. It also peaked at number 63 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]].\n\n==Music video==\nDespite the song not being released as an official single, the music video for the song first premiered twelve hours after the song's release, via the [[Reebok]] official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reebok.com/us/tlic|title=\"THE LIGHT IS COMING\" PREMIERE|accessdate=20 June 2018}}</ref> It was directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]], who had also directed the music video for Grande's \"[[No Tears Left to Cry]]\", and features \n[[Nicki Minaj]] performing her verse and [[Ariana Grande]] singing in a dimly-lit forest. The video was released worldwide on YouTube and Vevo the next day.\n\n==Live performances==\nGrande performed a preview of the song at [[Wango Tango]] on June 2, 2018 and was on the set list of her [[Sweetener World Tour]].<ref name=\"Rolling\"/>\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n'''Recording and management'''\n* Recorded at Glenwood Place Studios ([[Burbank, California]]), [[Jungle City Studios]] ([[New York City]]), [[Chalice Recording Studios]] ([[Hollywood]], [[California]]), The Lunchtable ([[Los Angeles]], California and [[Conway Recording Studios]] (Hollywood, California)\n* Nicki Minaj's vocals recorded at Germano Studios ([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])\n* Mastered at [[Sterling Sound]] (New York City, New York)\n* EMI Pop Music Publishing/More Water From Nazareth (GMR), Harajuku Barbie Music/Money Mack Music/Songs of Universal, Inc. (BMI), Universal Music Group Corp. (ASCAP)/GrandAriMusic (ASCAP)\n\n'''Personnel'''\n{{div col}}\n*[[Ariana Grande]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead vocals]], [[songwriting]]\n*[[Nicki Minaj]]&nbsp;\u2013 featured vocals, songwriting\n*[[Pharrell Williams]]&nbsp;\u2013 songwriting, [[music production|production]]\n*Mike Larson&nbsp;\u2013 [[audio recording|recording]], [[digital editing]], [[arrangement]], additional [[music programming|programming]]\n*Jacob Dennis&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Ramon Rivas&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Brendan Morawski&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Thomas Cullison&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Ben \u201cBengineer\u201d Sedano&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistant\n*Aubry \u201cBig Juice\u201d Delaine&nbsp;\u2013 Nicki Minaj's vocals recording\n*Kris Crawford&nbsp;\u2013 Nicki Minaj's recording assistant\n*Manny Park&nbsp;\u2013 Nicki Minaj's recording assistant\n*[[Manny Marroquin]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[audio mixing|mixing]]\n*Scott Desmarais&nbsp;\u2013 mix assistant\n*Chris Galland&nbsp;\u2013 mix assistant\n*Robin Florent&nbsp;\u2013 mix assistant\n*Randy Merrill&nbsp;\u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n{{div col end}}\n\nCredits adapte